                            @{b}@{u}@{fg highlight}SHORT INTRODUCTION@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

@{b}@{u}Disclaimer:@{ub}@{uu}   Use or don't use this program, it's your decision.  I will be
not  responsible  for  any damage!  I just can tell you, that I have tested
the  program  on  my machine and there was no problem, but I only guarantee
the usage of diskspace.  Short:  @{b}FREEWARE@{ub}

@{b}@{u}Why a short introduction:@{ub}@{uu}  The program is short and writing documents is
not my favorite waste of time.

@{b}@{u}Features:@{ub}@{uu}
* makes it possible to use Turboprint for dithering
* very fast (1.5MB picture takes about 3 seconds on my 68030@50)
* PasTex include-option
* style for including pictures in LaTeX

@{b}@{u}Why  this  program  exists:@{ub}@{uu}   My  friend  bought  Turboprint  (an excellent
printing-program)  and  had  a  lot  of  fun with it.  And then the problem
began:   Using  PaTeX  with  pictures  is very easy (using TeXpic), but the
ditheralgorithms  of  specialhost are not as good as the turboprintengines.
Second,  the loading of big pictures isn't possible, because datatypes will
be  used  (and  so  CHIP-Mem  is  the border).  Therefore he asked me for a
solution.  And here it is:  PCL2IFF!

@{b}@{u}Installation:@{ub}@{uu}   Put  the  right program (.000 for 68000, .030 for 68030 and
up)  wherever  you want in your path and that's it.  If you use the program
only with PasTex, tex:bin will be the best directory.

@{b}@{u}Working  with all programs:@{ub}@{uu}  First you start Turboprint, and work with your
pictures  as  usual.   Then you start the print-menu and choose TurboPrefs.
There  you  have  to install and activate the "HP Laserjet 5 series" driver
(that  has  nothing  to do with your destination printer), and activate the
"print  to  file"-option.   Then  return  to  the print-menu and print your
picture to the file.  Next you invoke PCL2IFF and convert the outputfile to
IFF.  That's it; you've converted any picture to a dithered bw-IFF!  If you
want to use the picture with PasTeX, you should use the DPI-option.

@{b}@{u}Program  usage:@{ub}@{uu}
The  program  can  only  be  run  from  the CLI.  Starting with ?  or wrong
arguments will show a little help.

For basic using, type "PCL2IFF infile outfile"

infile  is  the  Turboprint-outputfile and outfile is destination IFF-File;
sorry   there  is  no  patternmatching  (but  "list  lformat  ..."  or  the
standardscript  DPat (included with workbench) will help here).  The result
is the converted IFF-picture.

For using with PasTeX, type "PCL2IFF infile outfile DPI"

infile  and  outfile  are  the same as above, DPI is the used resolution of
your printer.  PCL2IFF will convert the picture to IFF and will generate an
include-file for PasTeX (like TeXpic).

@{b}@{u}Working with PasTeX and mypic.sty:@{ub}@{uu}
mypic.sty  is the style from TeXpic and therefore PCL2IFF produces the same
outputfiles.    To   see  the  file  in  your  TeX-documents,  type  \input
filename.tex  and  that's  it.   For better results use mypic.sty (for more
infos read mypic.sty).

@{b}@{u}Testing:@{ub}@{uu}   PCL2IFF is tested with files of Turboprint 6; please tell me the
behavior with other versions.

@{b}@{u}What  can  PCL2IFF not:@{ub}@{uu}  PCL2IFF is not a general PCL to IFF converter.  It
supports  at this time only standard mode 2 (TIFF) rastergraphics in a very
specific way.

@{b}@{u}Future:@{ub}@{uu}   If  you want some new features or have some errorreports, send it
to:

               Christian Beck <e9026778@stud3.tuwien.ac.at>

@{b}@{u}Last:@{ub}@{uu}   If you want some updates in the AMINET, than give me some response,
because  if  nobody  needs  this  program I will just develop it for my one
needing;  documents  (for  a  AMINET upload) makes work and I will not work
just for fun!


@endnode

